<H2><A NAME="SECTION00003000000000000000">
Generating Sets of Unforgeable Sequences</A>
</H2>

<P>
A side-product of this proof is a straightforward procedure for generating
unforgeable sequences.

<P>
If <IMG
 WIDTH="47" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img32.png"
 ALT="$ X(n)$"> is the set of unforgeable sequences of length <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$ n$">, then for odd <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$ n$"> we
can generate <IMG
 WIDTH="47" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img32.png"
 ALT="$ X(n)$"> from <IMG
 WIDTH="80" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img33.png"
 ALT="$ X(n-1)$"> as follows.  There are twice as many elements
in  <IMG
 WIDTH="47" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img32.png"
 ALT="$ X(n)$"> as <IMG
 WIDTH="80" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img33.png"
 ALT="$ X(n-1)$"> and they can be generated by taking each sequence from
<IMG
 WIDTH="80" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img33.png"
 ALT="$ X(n-1)$">, splitting it in half and then twice rebuilding it, once with
a zero in the middle and once with a one.

<P>
For even <IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img1.png"
 ALT="$ n$">, we can generate <IMG
 WIDTH="47" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img32.png"
 ALT="$ X(n)$"> from <IMG
 WIDTH="80" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img34.png"
 ALT="$ X(n-2)$"> by splitting
each sequence from <IMG
 WIDTH="80" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img34.png"
 ALT="$ X(n-2)$"> and putting a two digit sequence between
the two halves. This gives four times as many elements as in <IMG
 WIDTH="80" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img34.png"
 ALT="$ X(n-2)$">,
but some of the new ones are forgeable and must be removed.  These are
the ones where the first half of the sequence is the same as the second half
of the sequence or the half sequences themselves are forgeable (not elements of 
<IMG
 WIDTH="66" HEIGHT="37" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="img35.png"
 ALT="$ X(n/2)$">).

<P>
